      <section id="uid37">
        <title>Bit Error Rate (BER) and Gray Coding</title>
        <para id="id266524">With an <emphasis effect="italics">M</emphasis>-ary alphabet, there are <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mo form="prefix">log</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>M</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> bits per symbol,
so 1 symbol error could cause up to <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mo form="prefix">log</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mi>M</m:mi></m:mrow></m:math> bit errors.</para>
        <para id="id266577"><emphasis effect="italics">Gray coding</emphasis> is a clever way of mapping bits to symbols so
that neighboring symbols differ by only a single bit.
Since the vast majority of errors occur when <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>[</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi><m:mo>]</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> falls into a
neighboring decision region, Gray coding yields BER <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mo>≈</m:mo></m:math> SER.</para>
